Rating: 4
Really lovely, light and yummy! Nice to have a recipe that you can prep the night before and pop in the oven in the morning while making time for guests. However, timing wise that is not exactly how it worked out. I only give positive reviews to recipes I make changes to. I love reading the reviews and picking and choosing the alterations. So, here goes. I chose to use sauteed spinach (a 10 oz bag of salad) with garlic and shallots in place of the broccoli and I did this the night before I was to serve. I grated the cheese the night before, too. I did dry out the english muffins but it ended up being almost 24 hours. I did not assemble this the night before as intended. Since the muffins were so dry (and I did not have time for the custard to soak overnight) I cut the bottoms into 1 pieces for the base layer. I chopped the Canadian bacon but did not saute. I did not use hard boiled eggs, I cracked 6 raw eggs over my spinach and poked a knife through the yolk. I doubled the lemon juice in the custard and added a couple of pinches of fresh nutmeg. I chopped the muffin tops into tiny pieces and tossed it with melted butter to sprinkle over the top of the casserole (again, I did not have the time for the custard to soak into the top and thought it would be much easier to cut to serve). I only let it sit in the refrigerator for an hour before baking. I baked covered for 30 minutes, uncovered for 10 minutes (crisped the top a bit - a good thing) for my casserole to be done. Let it sit for 10 minutes before serving. I bet asparagus would be awesome - when it is fresh, in season and affordable. Definitely, saving this one.

