Rating: 3
The first time I made this I lowered the fat by using lite Jarlsberg, 2 percent milk and evaporated skim milk instead of cream. Otherwise I followed the recipe exactly and refrigerated about 12 hours. The result tasted good and the custard set up well but the bottom layer of english muffins turned into soggy mush. I also thought the hard-boiled eggs were too dominant. The next time I used the same lowfat subs but only two hard-boiled eggs, and I only refrigerated for two hours. It was still tasty and this time you could identify the english muffins. I also topped with buttered crumbs rather than quartered muffins and much preferred that. A good brunch or make-ahead breakfast that keeps and reheats well.

